</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>January Briefly Noted</title>
</head>
<body>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="O" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<center>
<img src="/crc/bn/bn.gif"><br>
</center>
<h2>Briefly Noted</h2>
<h3>January 1997</h3>
<br>
<p>
Three Senators and a Wedding:  Outgoing Kansas Senator Nancy Kassebaum and former Senate Majority Leader Howard Baker were
married on December 7 in Washington, with the ceremony performed by Rev. John C. Danforth, an Episcopal priest and former
Missouri Senator.  The bride, co-author of the Kassebaum-Kennedy health care legislation enacted earlier this year, announced
that after leaving office in January she will join the boards of the ROBERT WOOD JOHNSON FOUNDATION and the KAISER FOUNDATION.
[<i>New York Times</i>, weddings section]
<HR>
<P>
<P>Bowing to pressure from animal rights activists, the National Park Service will not use live reindeer at this year's
Christmas Pageant for Peace on the ellipse.  The protests came from PEOPLE FOR THE ETHICAL TREATMENT OF ANIMALS and the
WASHINGTON HUMANE SOCIETY.  PETA cited the &quot;stress&quot; which the reindeer undergo, and a spokesman for the HUMANE
SOCIETY said, &quot;Animals don't like to be trucked around.  They appreciate a steady place and a steady routine.&quot;
Normally, the nine deer stood around grazing on hay.  Merry Christmas.  [<i>Washington Post</i>]
<hr>
<P>
<P>The CAMPAIGN FOR HUMAN DEVELOPMENT, the American Catholic bishops anti-poverty program, has a new executive director:
Father Robert J. Vitillo from Paterson, New Jersey.  Father Vitillo is currently the delegate to the United Nations for
CARITAS INTERNATIONALIS, a federation of Catholic charitable agencies around the world.  He has worked with the group
since 1986, prior to which he was in charge of social ministries at the Paterson Diocese.  The top job at CHD has been
vacant for over a year since the departure of Father Joseph Hacala, S.J.
<HR>
<P>
<P>MICROSOFT CORP. has become the nation's leading corporate giver, with contributions totalling $73,211,927 for fiscal
year 1995-1996.  Microsoft was followed by JOHNSON & JOHNSON ($72.8 million) and IBM ($72.1 million).  Most of Microsoft's
contributions were in the form of software.  [<i>Corporate Giving Watch</i>]
<HR>
<P>
<P>FAMILY RESEARCH COUNCIL has published a &quot;Moms and Dads Survival Guide&quot; to help parents direct their children's
education.  It provides parents with an overview of current education trends and options.  It features reports on parental
rights, religious freedom in schools, GOALS 2000, and teachers unions.  The Guide also includes a contact list of private,
religious, and homeschool groups that parents can contact for more information.  Contact FRC: 800-225-4008.
<HR>
<P>
<P>Former Clinton administration Commerce Department official Douglas Hall is the new vice president and chief operating
officer for the NATURE CONSERVANCY, the huge environmental group based in Arlington, Virginia.  At Commerce, Hall had been
assistant secretary for oceans and atmosphere and also deputy administrator of the National Oceanographic and Atmospheric
Administration.  Lisa R. Davis, deputy press secretary for the Clinton-Gore campaign, will be the new media relations
director for the AMERICAN ASSOCIATION OF RETIRED PERSONS.  [<i>National Journal</i>]
<HR>
<P>
<P>The NATIONAL AND LEGAL POLICY CENTER notes that the AMERICAN BAR ASSOCIATION's top legislative priority during the 104th
Congress was saving the federally-funded LEGAL SERVICES CORPORATION, a prime source of funds for the litigious left.  The
ABA spent over $300,000 on its efforts, hired a full time lobbyist for the project, and arranged for thousands of members
to visit Congressional offices.
<HR>
<P>
<P>Margaret Ratner, the widow of radical left lawyer William Kunstler, and Ronald Kuby, Kunstler's factotum and putative
partner, are engaged in a legal battle over the right to Kunstler's name, files, and law practice.  Kunstler, infamous
lawyer for the Chicago Seven, failed to leave clear instructions regarding what would happen to his law firm.  Ms. Ratner,
herself a lawyer for various far left causes, has sued Mr. Kuby.  And he has filed an ethics complaint against her relating
to the confidentiality of Kunstler's files.  [<i>New York Times</i>]
<HR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
