<HTML>
<TITLE>1994 Annual Report - Publications -- Heritage</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2><I><FONT SIZE = "+3">P</FONT>ublications</I></H2></CENTER>

<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 30%>
Ideas count - and the best way to express ideas remains the written word. Heritage 
offered Washington lots of words in 1994,  publishing more than 250 books, 
monographs, and policy studies. The papers ranged from brief commentaries to 
5,000-to-10,000-word "Backgrounders" and lengthier monographs, such as 
"<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/issu.html">Issues 
'94: The Candidate's Briefing Book</a>," "A Citizen's Guide to Regulation," and 
"
"<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/indx.html">The Index of Economic Freedom</a>," a 1995 publication released in December. Regular 
newsletters included "Heritage Today" and  "Heritage Members News," featuring 
information about Heritage Foundation people and activities; "The Insider," 
reporting on publications and activities of Resource Bank groups; "Business/Education 
Insider," focusing on the role of business in education reform; and "Reforming 
Congress: Changing the Way Washington Works," which kept a watchful eye on 
the wayward Congress.
<P>
While Heritage research papers are provided free of charge to the policy-making 
community, there is great demand beyond that. In addition to printed copies, 
most Heritage policy studies also are available electronically on the NEXIS 
data-retrieval system and <a href="http://www.townhall.com">Town Hall</a>, the conservative computer network co-owned 
by Heritage and National Review. Town Hall operates as a private forum on CompuServe. 
Some Heritage publications are available additionally on audiotape. 

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">P</FONT>olicy <FONT SIZE = "+2">R</FONT>eview</H3></CENTER>

Heritage's flagship publication is <a href="/heritage/p_review/welcome.html">Policy Review</a>. Sprightly and unpredictable, 
Policy Review reached an all-time high in paid circulation in 1994: 30,000, 
a 30 percent  increase over the previous year. 
<p>
Policy Review's impact, however, continued to exceed its circulation. The summer 
issue, for example, featured a prescient article, "Flanagan's Island: How Boys 
Town Rescues Troubled Teens." Following the GOP sweep in November's congressional 
elections, Boys Town became a symbol for the kind of "tough love" proposed 
in the GOP's welfare-reform plan. The spring issue featured an article by Houston 
constable Victor Trevino, "Zebra Territory: The Courage of Houston's Volunteer 
Cops." A Mexican immigrant, Trevino told how he has organized volunteer patrols 
in his district, cutting truancy in half and crime by 10 percent without increasing 
taxes. The fall issue featured a headline-making article by  Rush Limbaugh: 
"Voice of America: Why Liberals Fear Me."  Excerpts appeared in the Sunday 
Los Angeles Times and dozens of other newspapers. The talk-radio phenomenon 
had been explored earlier in the year in "The Gurus of Gab," a lively symposium 
featuring 10 of America's top talkers. Among the prominent political figures 
with 1994 Policy Review bylines were Rep. Dick Armey (R-TX); Sen. Phil Gramm 
(R-TX); Rep. Henry Hyde (R-IL); and Jersey City Mayor Bret Schundler.  

<p>
Subscribe to <a href="/heritage/p_review/subscribe.html">Policy Review</a>
<BR>
<BR>
Go to the <A HREF="/townhall/townhall_shop/thpubs.html">Bookstore</A>.



