<HTML>
<TITLE>1994 Annual Report - Marketing -- Heritage</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2><I><FONT SIZE = "+3">M</FONT>arketing</I></H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>Popularizing Conservative Ideas</B></CENTER><P>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 30%>


<P>
On Nov. 8, 1994, a conservative tide swept across America - opening a new chapter 
in the political revolution launched by President Reagan 14 years earlier.
<P>
The White House, national news media, and Washington's liberal establishment 
were surprised by both the depth and the breadth of the conservative victory. 
They were even more surprised, however, by something else: that the voters 
both understood and supported the ideas proposed during the campaign by conservative 
candidates. 
<P>
They shouldn't have been surprised. Many of the specific proposals had been 
developed at The Heritage Foundation, and almost all of them had been time-tested 
in the court of public opinion: in speeches to business and civic groups, in 
congressional Town Hall meetings, in op-ed page articles, and on talk radio. 
Maybe the Washington establishment didn't appreciate the common-sense appeal 
of the conservative policy agenda, but the voters did.
<P>
Since 1973, The Heritage Foundation has served a dual role: both as an idea 
factory and as a product-testing laboratory. The first role - policy research, 
development, and innovation - is the purpose of Heritage's ongoing research 
program. The equally important second role of popularizing and legitimizing 
Heritage Foundation policy prescriptions and the broader conservative vision 
of government is the mandate of Heritage's marketing program. 
<P>
This emphasis on marketing to Congress and the Executive Branch, the national 
and international news media, state government officials, and the business, 
academic, and policy communities is one of the things that makes Heritage different 
from other policy institutes. As a USA Today headline put it in a post-election 
feature about Heritage, "The Think Tank: Foundation bringing vision back to 
the future."
<p>


<P>
<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">G</FONT>overnment <FONT SIZE = "+2">R</FONT>elations</H3></CENTER>
<P>
On November 21, two weeks after the election, Harvard University's John F. 
Kennedy School of Government announced it had cancelled its "Introduction to 
Congress" class in December. The Ivy League university had held the course 
for newly elected members of Congress for 22 years.  In 1994, there wasn't 
much interest in what the Harvard faculty might have to say. Instead, most 
congressional freshmen attended The Heritage Foundation's orientation program 
in Baltimore.
<P>
The Economist modestly called the change "a sign of the times." Earlier in 
the year, in its Jan. 7, 1994, issue, The Economist had forecast such a shift. 
"In the 1960s it looked as if universities would establish a monopoly over 
the life of the mind, providing policies for politicians, sinecures for writers, 
ideas for journalists and breakthroughs for industrialists." The 1980s, The 
Economist observed, "changed all that." Now, the editors wrote, governments 
in search of advice increasingly look "to think tanks such as the Institute 
of Economic Affairs in Britain and the Heritage Foundation in Washington, rather 
than to Oxford or Harvard." 
<P>

From the beginning, Congress - which has the constitutional authority to pass 
laws, ratify treaties, declare war, and approve spending - has been Heritage's 
primary audience. The government relations staff serves as an institutional 
link between the Heritage research team and the policymaking community, providing 
Congress and the Executive Branch with timely information and policy recommendations 
on matters of current interest.
<P>
<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">C</FONT>andidate <FONT SIZE = "+2">E</FONT>ducation</H3></CENTER>
<P>
With an important national election ahead, Heritage welcomed the 1994 political 
season with its 296-page candidates' briefing book, "Issues '94." The book 
was distributed free of charge to incumbents and challengers alike.  
<P>
Dozens of House and Senate candidates and several gubernatorial candidates, 
including George Pataki, who unseated New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, used the briefing 
book. As one successful congressional challenger, Ron Lewis (R-KY), wrote, 
"Heritage provided the best, most accurate facts and figures that I used in 
my campaign. They were right on target every time."
<P>

<P>

Heritage's efforts to provide policy guidance to future members of the 104th 
Congress didn't cease with the election. Most successful candidates had promised 
to challenge the status quo and cut Washington down to size. The three-day 
orientation conference offered by Heritage and Empower America provided a game 
plan for doing just that, with sessions on family tax relief, federal mandates 
and federalism, farm policy reform, fighting crime, congressional reform, health 
care, foreign policy, welfare reform, rebuilding America's defenses, the environmental 
activists' "green agenda," and cutting government. addition to the many Heritage 
analysts on the program, the list of speakers included Heritage Distinguished 
Fellows <a href="/heritage/staff/bennett.htm">William Bennett</a> and <a href="/heritage/staff/kemp.htm">Jack Kemp</a>, Sen. Malcolm Wallop (R-WY),  Rep. W.J. 
"Billy" Tauzin (D-LA), Virginia Secretary of Natural Resources Becky Norton 
Dunlop, Kemper Financial Services Senior Economist John Silvia, John DiIulio 
of The Brookings Institution, Rep. Cal Dooley (D-CA), former U.S. Ambassador 
to the United Nations Jeane Kirkpatrick, and talk show superstar Rush Limbaugh, 
who was named an "Honorary Member" of the 104th Congress's freshman class. 
<P>
<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">U.S.</FONT> <FONT SIZE = "+2">C</FONT>ongress 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">P</FONT>roject</H3></CENTER>
<P>
Seven years of intense, focused effort which included two landmark books and 
dozens of articles, papers, and seminars was rewarded in 1994 as House Republicans 
embraced most of the institutional reforms proposed by Heritage's U.S. Congress 
Assessment Project staff.
<P>
The 1988 Heritage book, "<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/imp.html">The Imperial Congress</a>," launched the debate. Something 
is terribly wrong with Congress, the book argued, and it needs to be fixed. 
As just one example, the book listed more than a dozen federal laws, including 
the National Labor Relations Act, Fair Labor Standards Act, Minimum Wage Act, 
Civil Rights Act of 1964, Freedom of Information Act, Occupational Safety and 
Health Act, Equal Employment Opportunity Act, and Ethics in Government Act, 
from which Congress had exempted itself.
<P>
All of the specific reforms approved by Congress on Jan. 4-5, 1995, can be 
found in the pages of "The Imperial Congress," the 1993 Heritage sequel, "<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/imp.html">The 
Ruling Class</a>," or in the many papers produced in 1994 and prior years by David 
Mason and the "Congress Project" staff. For example, at the top of House Speaker 
Newt Gingrich's list of reforms was a promise, spelled out in the "Contract 
with America," to make "all laws that apply to the rest of the country also 
apply equally to the Congress." The new majority also moved to reduce the number 
of congressional committees and subcommittees, cut committee staff, limit the 
terms of committee chairs, open committee meetings to the public, and eliminate 
the phony "baseline budgeting" scam, which for years had allowed Washington 
to act as if it were cutting spending when it really was increasing it.
<P>

<P>

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">G</FONT>overnors' <FONT SIZE = "+2">F</FONT>orum</H3></CENTER>
<P>
Heritage's Governors' Forum continued its efforts in 1994 to involve governors 
and state administrators more directly in federal policy decisions affecting 
their states. With the new Congress promising to return many government functions 
to the states, the program in 1995 will increase its emphasis on the concept 
of federalism.
<P>

<P>
Just two years old, the program already is seen as a major national forum. 
California Gov. Pete Wilson, for example, appeared at Heritage just days after 
his come-from-behind reelection. Seen by some as the start of a potential 1996 
presidential bid, his hard-hitting speech addressed the imbalance between state 
and federal government and how state executives can help take back some of 
the powers wrongly assumed by Washington. Other Governors' Forum speakers in 
1994 included former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, Virginia Gov. George Allen 
Jr., and Mississippi Gov. Kirk Fordice.
<P>
</DOC>
<DOC>
