appears in <b>USA Today</b>.
<p>
<b>Jan. 3</b> - FRC Vice President for Policy William R. Mattox, Jr.'s
op-ed, &quot;Numbers Game Masks Illegitimacy Problems,&quot; appears in 
<i>USA Today</i>.
<p>
<b>Jan. 5</b> - Marty Dannenfelser, FRC's Government Relations Director,
is quoted on the front page of <i>The Wall Street Journal></i> regarding 
the federal shutdown.
<p></ul>
<li><b>FRC on Air</b>
<p><ul>
<b>Jan. 3</b> - CBS Evening News &quot;Eye on America&quot; segment featured
FRC's Robert Knight on the Kinsey research (<i>see</i> News Watch) and 
showed part of our documentary, <i>The Children of Table 34</i>.
</ul><p><hr><p>
<a name="gary">
<center><h2><font size=+3>I</font>NSIDE <font size=+3>D.C.</font></h2></center>
<p><hr width=30% size=2><p>
<center><font size=+2><b><i>Hope Is a Hand-up</i></b></font><br>
by Gary L. Bauer</center>
<p>
<font size=+3>J</font>ust before Christmas, Family Research Council hosted 
an important event in Washington.  It was a one-day conference, with 
distinguished speakers like authors Michael Novak and Dr. Marvin
Olasky.  The conference was devoted to the tragedy of poverty, with a 
close look at the tricky question of welfare reform.
<p>
I'm more convinced than ever that we must look with new eyes at
the scale of this tragedy.  It's really not enough to say that certain 
kinds of welfare reform will cause suffering.  We have to come to terms 
with the degree of suffering that is happening right now -- and not just 
suffering from material want, but from the sense of purposelessness that
saps the human spirit.
<p>
Those of us who believe most fiercely in the durability of traditional
values are precisely the ones to stand up now and say that every individual 
has qualities that no welfare system should be allowed to destroy. FRC 
recognizes that the best and most compassionate help comes from
private individuals who build personal relationships and offer
material support simultaneously. A hand-up not a handout. The premise is 
that needy individuals are not &quot;clients,&quot; but fellow human
beings.
<p>
America cannot implement neat, clean, top-down policies that will
jumpstart a network of caring in every community.  Instead, each of us must 
take direct action to heal the hurt -- not at the ballot box, but in our 
neighborhoods and communities as we minister daily to needy individuals.
<p>
One happy byproduct is that our own children, by watching our
example, will grow to appreciate what is great and good.  Even strong 
parents depend on the interplay of thoughtful neighbors to help pattern 
right habits of the heart.
<p>
FRC is taking the initiative to encourage a new ethic of caring
because, I believe, social conservatives are the very people who have the 
idealism and initiative to build up a new network of helping institutions. 
As we have begun to speak out, we have discovered that the scale of the
crisis is an unprecedented opportunity for us to demonstrate, in full 
technicolor action, a fundamental truth:  Traditional values are traditional 
because they are functional.
<p><hr width=45% size=2><p>
<center><i><font size=+2>TRADITIONAL VALUES<br>
ARE<br>
FUNCTIONAL VALUES</font></i></center>
<p><hr width=45% size=2><p>
When nothing else moves the needle, God's ways work.  His love
binds up wounds.  Our service to those who are hurting is one of the most 
obvious means we have at our disposal to let earth know what heaven looks like. 
God's love looks most beautiful, in fact, against a backdrop of despair.
<p>
Dr. Virgil Gulker, founder of Kids Hope USA, tells a story about
one small step in a child's journey to God.  Kids Hope USA aims to link adult 
volunteers in one-to-one relationships with at-risk children. This Christmas 
season, one volunteer took &quot;her child&quot; to see a Christmas pageant
at her church that included a living nativity.  As Mary, Joseph,
and the baby Jesus took their places, the child Amanda turned to her new 
friend and asked with wide eyes, &quot;Is this real?&quot;  The volunteer 
replied, &quot;Oh yes, Amanda, it's very real.&quot;
<p>
That moment almost undoubtedly left a mark on Amanda's soul. In time, 
I suspect, she will be much more likely to regard that scene as real 
because one of God's loving servants was sitting by her side.
<p>
<i>If you would like to come alongside a child who needs you, but
don't know how, please call our office at 1-800-225-4008 for more 
information. You can also request a copy of new FRC resources on 
welfare reform.  The enclosed card has all the details.</i>
<p><hr><p>
<a name="horizon">
<center><h2><font size=+3>O</font>N THE <font size=+3>H</font>ORIZON</h2></center>
<p>
<li><b>Twisting the Knot.</b> Hawaiian state <b>commission appointed by governor
voted 5-2 in December to endorse same-sex &quot;marriage,&quot;</b> setting stage
for state court decision on issue in July.  Two <b>commissioners issued dissenting 
report</b>.  They have also sued commission, charging majority with <b>suppressing 
information, holding unauthorized meetings</b>, and other failures. Meanwhile, 
South Dakota and other states are moving to join Utah in <b>passing legislation
protecting integrity of marriage license laws</b>, should Hawaii legalize
homosexual nuptials.
<p><hr><p>
<a name="freshmen">
<center><h2><font size=+3>F</font>RESH <font size=+3>A</font>IR</h2></center>
<p>
Freshmen members of the House of Representatives are in the media
glare as the budget dispute continues between Congress and the White House. 
The first-termers have been called both &quot;principled citizen 
legislators&quot; and &quot;inflexible extremists.&quot; What's the 
reality?
<p>
Nearly all of the freshmen have strongly endorsed term limits
and committed to do what they think is right, regardless of short-term 
political consequences. They want a balanced budget and tax relief for 
America's families.  Their insistence on these policies led to stronger 
agreements with the Senate than first seemed possible.  They have been 
just as tough in negotiations with the White House.
<p>
Moreover, despite President Clinton's opposition, the freshmen
have helped to restore two abortion limitations that were overturned 
during the last Congress: limits on abortion funding through federal 
health insurance programs and a ban on elective abortions in overseas 
military hospitals.
<p>
Freshmen House members also helped sidetrack a bill to fully fund
the National Endowment for the Arts (NEA).  Their efforts forced the House 
leadership to zero out NEA funding within two years.
<p>
The principles of this freshman class will be further demonstrated
in 1996 as they strive to move parental rights and religious liberties 
legislation through Congress. They are truly making a difference on issues 
vital to pro-family Americans.
<p><hr size=2><p>
