<title>QA Forum</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFCC" text="#000000">

<p><strong>Subject: Literal interpretation of the bible </strong></p>

<p>We need to let the Bible be it's own expositor. When we
encounter a text that we cannot understand we need to put it
aside for the moment, continue with the entire passage (to
understand the context) and then come back and fill in the pieces
by finding other references of the text in question. Since the
Bible was written by a diverse group of writers, we need to
understand that each wrote in his own style. On the surface it
might appear that there are contradictions in the Bible, yet when
the reader is attentive and respectfully uncover the fundamental
harmony. The Bible, like most things, comes with
&quot;rules&quot; if you please, which by careful application of
these rules and guidance of the Holy Spirit, God's treasures are
revealed. One such &quot;rules&quot; is pertains to literal vs.
symbolic interpretation. Interpret the text as literal when the
context does not use any symbolic language (beasts, horns, etc.)
When symbols are used, we need to interpret them as how the Bible
has defined these symbols and when time is involved, use
prophetic time periods (day-year principle Ez. 4:6, etc.). </p>

<p>Do not give up! Sincere devotion and prayer will guide your
understanding. </p>

<p>sincerely, sreyes </p>

