<body bgcolor="#FFFFCC" text="#000000">

<p>Subject: My son is schizophrenic</p>

<p>From: Carol Wilson<br>
Marrero, LA<br>
<br>
To whom it may concern:<br>
<br>
With a heavy heart and dwindling hope, I once again sit down to
send a<br>
fresh batch of letters out to anyone I can find in hope that
somewhere<br>
someone will listen and help me save my son. This is not a letter<br>
requesting funds but one requesting public support.<br>
<br>
We are the parents of a 15 year old boy who was diagnosed 2 years
ago<br>
with schizoaffective disorder/schizophrenia. This summer, we
learned he<br>
also has a genetic condition known as Klinefelter Syndrome.
Klinefelter<br>
Syndrome males have cells with the genetic chromosomal makeup of
47,XXY<br>
as opposed to 46,XY. Our son is a mosaic with 47,XXY on 93% of
his cells<br>
and 46,XY on the other 7%. The condition causes hypogonadism,
among<br>
other things, and requires testosterone replacement therapies.<br>
<br>
Due to his psychiatric history, I have found doctors are
unwilling to<br>
treat his low testosterone levels on an outpatient basis, and
medically<br>
necessary treatment is withheld. There is also a pharmacological
by-play<br>
that occurs with hormones and anti-psychotics, so doctors have to
be very<br>
careful to all work together to treat this young man in a
specialized<br>
way.<br>
<br>
Two years ago when our son was first diagnosed with
schizoaffective<br>
disorder, the Louisiana state psychiatrist, Dr. Charmaine
Semenuik, who<br>
had the courage to make such a diagnosis on one so young told us
he was<br>
in need of the structure and care a residential facility provided
and<br>
that we could not afford to pay for his treatments. We were not
ready to<br>
believe that, so we have spent the last two years and great sums
of money<br>
to obtain treatments and to maintain him at home and in the
community.<br>
But faith died in the face of reality.<br>
<br>
Now, 9 hospitalizations and thousands of dollars later, we have
come to<br>
realize our son must get the level of care intermediate placement
in a<br>
neuro-psychiatric facility will provide so that one day he will
be able<br>
to live in the community. His current outpatient psychiatrist,
Dr.<br>
Padmini Nagaraj, as well as his former doctor, Dr. Robert
Detrinis, have<br>
both told us our son needs this high level of care. At the
National<br>
Institutes of Health, our son was determined to be
multi-dimensionally<br>
impaired and of a small group of children who need the services
of a<br>
highly structured program for a while to achieve success.
Additionally,<br>
Dr. Mark Forman of Tulane Medical Center did an evaluation and
concurs<br>
with everyone's findings. We love our son dearly and have not
wanted to<br>
send him away for treatment, but there comes a time when love is
strong<br>
enough to make a tough decision.<br>
<br>
Sadly, our state does not offer such services. Further, the
insurance<br>
we have through my husband's company does not have good coverage
for<br>
mental illness issues and will not cover this level of care. I
guess<br>
Medicaid wasted so much money on fraudulent long-term psychiatric<br>
services (as evidenced by the Times-Picayune series by Chris
Adams,<br>
&quot;Medicaid Madness,&quot; written last year)and is moving
toward in home<br>
neuropsychiatric placements only, regardless of the clinical
condition,<br>
with supposed services in the community, that they have cut
entirely the<br>
program to finance intermediate neuropsychiatric care.<br>
<br>
Also, my son only qualifies for Medicaid when out of the home for
30 days<br>
or more, so community services are not available to us, and we
cannot<br>
afford private ones. The waiver programs that waive parental
income for<br>
the children's Medicaid provision are for the developmentally
disabled<br>
only, and even there, it is a waiting list of about 9,000, but
those<br>
families are able to access supports and services denied to us.
So in<br>
the community, my son will be where he has been for the last 2
years,<br>
without services or support except 30 days per year acute care in
a<br>
psychiatric hospital through our private insurance to stabilize
acute<br>
episodes and not to rehabilitate his condition and condition him
to med<br>
compliance, and he also will be allowed 50 medicine checks per
year with<br>
a psychiatrist. Not to mention that quite a few of the programs
for his<br>
diagnosis are for those 18 or older. For two years, I have
written<br>
letters, made phone calls, and knocked on doors to locate support
and<br>
services only to be denied.<br>
<br>
Although we have located an appropriate placement in Austin,
Texas, where<br>
they are experienced in treating boys of both of our son's
particular<br>
diagnoses and where they are a Louisiana Medicaid provider, there
are no<br>
funds or coverage for treatment. Medicaid coverage or state
coverage in<br>
this state for long-term care for adolescents falls into 3
categories:<br>
those with IQs below 65, those who were removed from violent or<br>
neglectful home environments, and juvenile offenders. Giving up
custody<br>
to the state would result in disaster for our son and the
services he<br>
needs not being accessed since he does not meet the above
criteria for<br>
placement. How can the state care for my son better than I can?<br>
<br>
Additionally, to accomplish such a thing, I would have to press
false<br>
charges against my son as an ungovernable juvenile, which in all<br>
likelihood would result in this incredibly naive and not very
street<br>
smart kid being placed in a juvenile residential facility for
deviant<br>
juveniles where he would be at risk to be taken advantage of or
to learn<br>
deviant behaviors. As things continue, without immediate
treatment, he<br>
will become entwined needlessly in the juvenile justice system
through<br>
misperception of a situation or he will fall prey to substance
abuse. It<br>
happens all the time, and we all know it. What a nightmare! The
thought<br>
of going such a route and losing my son in such a senseless
manner makes<br>
me quite ill.<br>
<br>
The service providers I believe are beginning to see our son's
need for<br>
an out of the home placement, but they are insisting I give up
custody<br>
and that he be placed in an inappropriate placement. I was told
recently<br>
that such placements as I seek in Texas would be available to us
if my<br>
son were a victim of brain trauma or brain injury. I contend that<br>
neurobiological brain disorders are the evidence of brain insult
of some<br>
type. I also feel it is not right for a federally funded program
such<br>
as Medicaid to pay for the developmentally disabled to receive
this level<br>
of service but not the psychiatrically disabled. Is that not in<br>
violation of the American's with Disablities Act? Were not the
federal<br>
guidelines written in such a way as to make states responsible
for the<br>
care of their mentally ill and not to exempt them from covering
these<br>
people?<br>
<br>
Somewhere we have to realize you cannot put a fiscal value on a
human<br>
life. Some way has to be found where my son can acquire Medicaid
or<br>
other coverage for the treatments he needs in Austin, Texas. And
some way<br>
must be found to approve him for services in Austin. At some
point, we<br>
have to stop passing out emotional bandaids and begin doing
advanced<br>
reconstructive surgery. Only then can we even hope to save this
young<br>
man's life. My husband is a professional and has a good job, but
with 5<br>
children, medical debt, assisting one child in college, and other<br>
necessities, the $400-$500 perday of our son's care is beyond us.
We<br>
have always been honest, solid, hard-working Americans. Why
should we be<br>
required to give up custody of our child because we cannot afford
medical<br>
care? Why should our child be denied appropriate medical care
because of<br>
the convenience of the state?<br>
<br>
When will we alleviate the suffering of the mentally ill with
timely and<br>
appropriate treatments and not base their care on financial
restraints?<br>
When will we begin to realize that mental illness left untreated
or not<br>
properly treated is a terminal illness too?<br>
<br>
I was informed Monday, October 21, that Louisiana Medicaid no
longer<br>
pays for intermediate residential psychiatric care for the<br>
psychiatrically disabled children or adolescents. I further have
been<br>
informed that the state of Louisiana will not assume
responsibility for<br>
his care either. I also am aware that at the facility in Texas
where my<br>
son is approved for treatment is a Louisiana girl there at the
expense of<br>
the state of Louisiana, but she is in custody of the state of
Louisiana.<br>
Again, why should parents have to yield custody to obtain
treatments?<br>
<br>
I am not asking for my son to be locked away. I am asking for
medically<br>
necessary treatments for 6 months to a year in a facility where
he would<br>
not be in a lockdown unit and could receive appropriate medical<br>
interventions that will save him from becoming another Michael
Cochran of<br>
the 48 Hours broadcast of October 24. He also will be in a
program to<br>
prepare him to live in the community. When he is 18, if he lives
that<br>
long and we are able to stabilize and rehabilitate him now, he
will be<br>
able to fully access available community supports and services on
his<br>
own, much better than we can for him at this time. As I read the
federal<br>
guidelines, minors under the age of 21 are the responsibility of
the<br>
state to provide coverage for on an inpatient basis (including<br>
residential care) for a mental illness if such care is deemed<br>
medically necessary and for a definite period of time and the
patient's<br>
condition is reasonably expected to improve to the point that
such<br>
inpatient care will no longer be necessary. The HCFA states that
the<br>
goal of the legislature was to leave the care of the mentally ill
with<br>
the state, but to provide Medicaid coverage for the mentally ill
under 21<br>
and over 65.<br>
<br>
Currently, my son is at Southeast State Mental Hospital where he
has been<br>
for the last month, and where through our efforts, we were able
to push<br>
for a lifting of time constraints since he is not stable enough
to return<br>
home. We were able to gain about 3 months while Dr. Forman
continues to<br>
monitor and evaluate his pharmacological condition and to see to
what<br>
extent he needs antipsychotics. However, Southeast does not have
the<br>
program to meet my son's needs beyond that 3 months, or even less
if they<br>
are able to establish a pharmacological program for my son. Four
days<br>
off all medications, and he has already gone from a model patient
to<br>
someone who has punched 2 holes in the wall. As Dr. Nagaraj has
written,<br>
his behavior problems are secondary to medication compliance.<br>
<br>
I have also spoken with Dr. Paul Balson, the chief psychiatrist
for the<br>
state of Louisiana, and found him to be compassionate and
intelligent and<br>
knowledgeable about the plight of the mentally ill in this state.
He has<br>
patiently explained to me that folks of my son's diagnosis have a
very<br>
difficult time in the family home without the structure and
emotional<br>
sterility necessary for stabilization.<br>
<br>
Most sources sincerely wish me luck in this fight for services,
but<br>
caution me about the impossibility of winning. I do not want to
have to<br>
move, as Dr. Ron Boudreaux of DHHS told me many folks have done
to<br>
secure medical treatments for a Louisiana citizen. When my son
becomes<br>
18, if things continue along this course this battle will become
even<br>
more impossible to win, and I will have lost a son to this
devastating<br>
disease.<br>
<br>
Even though he is retiring and leaving office, Senator Johnston's
office<br>
has been of a tremendous help and support. Constituent Services
of<br>
Governor Mike Foster's office informed me the governor could not
get<br>
involved because if he did for our family, he would have to for
every<br>
other family in the state of Louisiana. I guess I made the
mistake of<br>
thinking that the governor is elected to serve the needs of all
the<br>
people he represents. Perhaps your office will tell me the same
thing.<br>
Other state and federal legislators have ignored me, or I have
been told<br>
by their offices that there is nothing they can or will do.<br>
<br>
And, so, I write to you. Surely you must be able to know some way
we can<br>
keep this boy from being another sad statistic. Dr. Ron Boudreaux
of the<br>
Mental Health division of the Louisiana DHHS told me on Monday,
October<br>
28, that this level of care is no longer available in Louisiana
because<br>
&quot;it is not appropriate for the vast majority.&quot; But, all
these doctors<br>
who have clinically evaluated my son from the private, state, and<br>
national sectors cannot be wrong in saying he is one of the
minority for<br>
whom the level of care is a must. The vast majority of people do
not<br>
require the wheelchair ramps at the public library either, but
the ADA<br>
says they must be there for the minority. I contend this level of
care<br>
was never intended to be abolished by state programs but to be
there for<br>
that minority like my son who must have it. He did say he
instructed the<br>
providers in Jefferson Parish to give my son's case &quot;special<br>
consideration&quot; for community supports and services, but I
realize the<br>
extremely limited amount that is available to us will not be
enough, and<br>
we will be putting a bandaid on a situation in need of
reconstructive<br>
surgery. I also have to wonder who will give special
consideration to<br>
the other Dougs out there.<br>
<br>
Perhaps I am wasting my time, and those of you to whom I now
write will<br>
say with the service providers who, never having met my son or
clinically<br>
evaluated him or visited the facility I have found for his
medical<br>
treatments, feel that the doctors who have evaluated and treated
my son<br>
are wrong and that my son does not need this level of care.
Forgive me if<br>
I sound tired and angry and frustrated. I am all those things,
but I am<br>
also a mother who will move mountains if I have to for my child
and the<br>
minority of other children like him who cannot speak for
themselves.<br>
<br>
<br>
Thank you for your time and consideration.<br>
<br>
Sincerely,<br>
<br>
Carol Wilson<br>
cawilson@bellsouth.net<br>
<br>
</p>

