 magazine, family, children, books,">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>QA FORUM</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFCC" text="#000000">

<p>Subject: My son is schizophrenic</p>

<p>Dear Carol,<br>
Thank you for sharing the heartwrenching story of your son with
me. I have <br>
always thought that each of us suffers some type of mental
illness to one <br>
degree or another, in one form or another and for one period or
another in <br>
their life. For who is to determine what &quot;normal behavoir or
normal thoughts&quot; <br>
are?<br>
<br>
You mentioned your son punched two holes in the wall recently. So
did the <br>
father of my best friend when we were kids growing up. Yet he was
not <br>
considered mentally ill. I don't mean to trivialize your son's
situation. I <br>
only point out that each of us wrestles with anger, irrational
fear, confused <br>
thinking and a whole host of seemingly &quot;ucontrollable&quot;
thoughts of varying <br>
degrees every day. <br>
<br>
I believe that mental illness can be --though not most of the
time-- a <br>
physical imparment. But what causes it? Are some born with it?
Obviously, <br>
yes. And what of schizophrenia: are you born with it or is a
learned response <br>
to fear? Studies have shown that fear releases certain chemicals
in your <br>
brain. Is it possible that over time, these chemicals can alter
your <br>
nuerologic system? (please forgive any typos as I don't have
spell check). <br>
And if so, why are some people more predisposed to irrational
fear than <br>
others?<br>
<br>
In your letter you did not mention anything about your faith or
where God is <br>
in all of this. Because you wrote to me, I assume that you are a
believer in <br>
Christ or at least a believer but perhaps one who believes only
and trusts <br>
little.<br>
More importantly perhaps, you did not mention what your son's
faith is.<br>
<br>
Whether your son's condition is caused by a reaction to accute
irrational fear <br>
or by a physical imparment/handicap, God can help. God empowers
all kinds of <br>
people with severe physical and mental imparements to live
productive lives, <br>
or to at least, live in His peace. Certainly your son is aware of
his <br>
condition. Inbetween moments of acute behavior, what he THINKS
about his <br>
condition is almost certain to worsen it. I'm sure it has already
consumed <br>
his thought life. So much so, that he has developed all kinds of
&quot;misbeliefs&quot; <br>
about himself, such as:<br>
&quot;I'm partially mentally retarded and I cannot change&quot;,
or<br>
&quot;I'm schizophrenic and I cannot change&quot;, or<br>
&quot;I have an imbalance of hormones and I cannot change&quot;,
or<br>
&quot;I'm damaged goods and I can never adopt to it or be at
peace&quot; or<br>
&quot;God has forsaken me.&quot;<br>
<br>
Whatever physically mental imparements your son has, they are
probably <br>
magnified by the misbeliefs he has told himself about his
condition. May I <br>
suggest you and your son read the book &quot;Telling Yourself The
Truth&quot;. Just <br>
understanding this would be a great relief to him. You can order
it through <br>
our website CHRISTIANdigest.com or through any Christian
bookstore.<br>
<br>
Can your son be trained to control his thoughts and behavior
without the help <br>
of drugs? I believe he can. If Helen Keller who could not speak,
could not <br>
see and could not hear- and was emotionally &quot;out of
control&quot; with her thoughts <br>
and behavior, could learn to live at peace and live a productive
life, there <br>
is hope. Imagine being born into this world deaf, dumb and blind.
Let your <br>
mind imagine it for a moment. How miserable and hopeless it would
be to try <br>
to control your thoughts under such conditions. Now think of the
advantage <br>
your son has in that he can see, can hear and can speak. And
although his <br>
thinking is impaired, he can read and reason.<br>
<br>
Does your son know Jesus Christ? Does he have a relationship with
Him? Has <br>
your son relinqued total control of his life and thoughts to
Christ? Has he <br>
asked Christ to live in him?<br>
Does your son know that:<br>
&quot;I can do all things through Christ who strengthens me&quot;<br>
&quot;God has a plan for his life that is good and not evil&quot;<br>
<br>
I beleive that you can teach your son that although he has a
physical <br>
imparement that can cause confusion in his thinking (and hence
emotions and <br>
behavior), that he can learn to recognize the wrong thinking and
give those <br>
thoughts over to the Lord. And by all means, he can be taught not
to live a <br>
life waiting in apprehension of the next wave of confusion, but
to be <br>
proactive in his thinking. To make a conscious, willful effort to
fill his <br>
mind with the facts that God loves him. That God cares for him.
That Christ <br>
lives within him. That the Holy Spirit who Jesus calls the Spirit
of Truth, <br>
is ALWAYS with him, ready and able to help him with his thought
life. These <br>
are the facts. This is truth. Do you believe it? Does your son
believe It?<br>
<br>
He'll need lots of love and encouragement from you and especially
from his <br>
father his entire life. But I believe he can learn to live with
joy and at <br>
peace. With God, all things are possible. He may never run his
own company, <br>
but God does have a plan for him. Maybe it is working with
animals, maybe it <br>
is in counselling others with similiar challanges.<br>
<br>
If you haven't already done so, may I suggest that:<br>
1. You and your son and his dad if he will, get down on your
knees and commit <br>
the rest of your lives to Christ, each and every day.<br>
2. Believe and trust in the Lord to work out His plan in your
son's life.<br>
3. Seek Christian psychiatric counseling from the Minearth Meyer
clinic who by <br>
the way, deals with schizophrenia at 800 639-5433 or 972 907-1972<br>
4. Start educating your son on all the things he can do to keep
his thought <br>
life proactive on peaceful, truthful thoughts by reading the
Bible every day <br>
as well as other Christian counseling and living books.<br>
<br>
I will be praying for your son and your family.<br>
<br>
God Bless,<br>
<br>
Drew Lawler<br>
editor / CHRISTIANdigest<br>
<br>
<br>
</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

