<body BGCOLOR="#ffffcc" text="000000">

<P>Jay,<BR>
<BR>


The most loving and friendly thing a person could possibly
tell you is that you and she were in adultery and headed
for the lake of fire, according to God (Rev. 21:8). 
<BR>
<BR>

She does not have Scriptural grounds for divorce, according 
to the Lord Jesus (Matt. 5:32 and 19:9) and the Apostle
Paul (1 Cor. 7:10-15). 
<BR>
<BR>

You both need to repent and get saved. Ask God to have mercy
on you for your sexual immorality, and put this woman out of
your mind. She is right that it is not right in God's eyes
for you to live together or to be "married." If she 
divorces her husband, she must remain unmarried, as Paul
stated to the Corinthians.
<BR>
<BR>

If you are eligible for marriage, then you need to look for
someone else who is also eligible, and wait until AFTER you
are legitimately married IN GOD'S EYES before you have sex.
You do not want to be committing continuous adultery 
as Jesus spoke about.
<BR>
<BR>

This life is a test (Jam. 1:12; Rev. 2:10,11; 3:10). The
stakes are eternal. Only the minority will pass the test and
enter through the narrow gate that leads to life (Matt. 7:
13,14). The vast majority will be thrown into the lake of
fire (Rev. 20:15; 21:8). Don't get yourself snared by an
illegitimate marriage that may bring much temporal pleasure
and comfort now, but reap eternal torment in fire and
incredible regret over such later.
<BR>
<BR>

It is not always God's will to remarry as 1 Cor. 7:11 clearly
states.

<P>
