<body bgcolor="#FFFFCC" text="#000000">

<p>Subject: Divorce/Friendship <br>
</p>

<p>Dear Jay:</p>

<p>Anytime you are dealing with a person suffering through the
disintegration of a marriage, you're going to be dealing with a
roller coaster ride of emotions and doubts and pain. Since she
wants to try to reconcile with her husband, it is your duty as a
true friend to do all you can to help her in that endeavor, as
that would be the best possible outcome for her and her family
(barring the possibility of abuse). Divorce is a messy business,
and almost never in the best interests of anyone except perhaps
the Divorce Lawyers. It is very scary for a woman, especially
with young children, to face the possibility of life alone. You
were a convenient way-station for her...someone she chose to lean
on. It feels good to have someone need you, but sooner or later,
she has to make a decision. It is best that you not try too hard
to influence her against her husband, as you are now quite
prejudiced in your opinion, wanting her yourself. Back off, and
let her try to work things out...In marriage, a husband and wife
become &quot;One Flesh&quot;... If a marriage breaks up, it is
literlly tearing apart of that One Flesh...It is truly that
awful. We know. And even after healing, the scars from that
tearing will never completely go away. <br>
God Bless you and have a Joyful Christmas<br>
J&amp;D<br>
<br>
</p>

