<p>Subject: <a href="qaMsg46.htm">Divorce for the believer</a> /
Posted by <a href="mailto:Nolan@albany.net">Nolan@albany.net</a>
(Diane Nolan)</p>

<p>My husband and I have a very solid, happy, christian marriage.
Every day we thank the Lord together for the miracle he worked in
allowing us to find one another. We are at peace with one another
and active in our church. </p>

<p>We have both been married and divorced before. Both were very
early marriages, both ended over 10 years ago, and both
ex-spouses have remarried happily and now have children. Both
divorces were mutually agreed upon by both parties at the time. I
should add that my husband and I met a couple of years ago...we
are from different states originally and were not acquainted at
the time of our divorces. </p>

<p>Anyway, we are doing the best we can. I do not believe in my
heart that Jesus actually intended for me (I am 31) or for that
matter, my husband, to live out the rest of our days alone. </p>

<p>I think that being a christian family is God's will for us. </p>

<p>I simply think that the dogmatic, legalistic viewpoint held by
a certain group who has posted a message on this forum
exemplifies a judgemental, and negative, hate-filled viewpoint. </p>

<p>What would that writer have us do...divorce each other now?
Break up the families of our ex-spouses and remarry people who
are virtual strangers now? </p>

<p>Excuse my impassioned response, but I believe in the God of
salvation from sin, redemption, forgiveness, mercy, grace... need
I go on? The Jesus who forgave the woman at the well of her
previous 4 marriages...the God of second chances... and of love,
a &quot;friend that sticketh closer than a brother&quot; and who
expects us to make the most of the life he has given us, even if
that means messing up as a teenager and starting over again. </p>

<p>Thank you. </p>

