<body bgcolor="#FFFFCC" text="#000000">

<p>Subject: Marriage</p>

<p><br>
Dana - </p>

<p>If indeed, this young lady's husband divorced her because he
got involved in an adulterous relationship (How else would he
have discovered his new sexual preference?) She has grounds,
Biblically speaking, for her divorce. Despite this, she is still
going to suffer great pain and grief over the tearing of her
marriage bonds. Healing is slow, no matter who is at
&quot;fault&quot; Find the counsel of a mature Christian friend
or pastor, as divorce is a rocky road for a believer, and often
other Christians throw more stumbling blocks in the way of your
recovery. </p>

<p>Keep in mind what the Bible says about marriage. It is where
two are made &quot;One Flesh&quot;. If you plan to marry, realize
that the tearing apart of that union will leave its scars. A new
marriage is an attempt to reenter into a relationship of Oneness.
The bond is precious, but as you know, not impervious. The bonds
of your friend's marriage were broken by her unfaithful spouse.
She is not guilty. But she is wounded. Treat her kindly and let
the Spirit guide you as you develop your friendship. Don't rush
into marriage, it will not heal the wounds...If you are meant to
marry, you will know...be patient. And keep praying! Have a
blessed new year. </p>

<p>DAN </p>

