<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="keywords"
content="christianity, Christ, religion, magazines,
 magazine, family, children, books,">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>QA Forum</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFCC" text="#000000">

<p><strong>Subject: Adultery, Divorce and Remarriage from the
Bible </strong></p>

<p>As a person who has spent thousands of hours reading and
studying the Bible, the following is my input: </p>

<p>(1) To divorce over &quot;incompatibility and neglect&quot; is
not a legitimate reason according to the Word of God! Please note
Matt. 5:32: </p>

<p>&quot;But I tell you that anyone who divorces his wife, except
for marital unfaithfulness, causes her to commit adultery, and
anyone who marries a woman so divorced commits adultery.&quot; </p>

<p>Similarly, Matt. 19:9 says: </p>

<p>&quot;I tell you that anyone who divorces his wife, except for
marital unfaithfulness, and marries another woman commits
adultery.&quot; </p>

<p>These statements about divorce and remarriage were given by
the Lord Jesus. Clearly, He stated marital unfaithfulness (sexual
immorality) is the only cause for a divorce! Hence, if one
divorces his spouse for any other reason besides sexual
immorality, regardless what that reason is, he is indicted by
these verses! If such a person would then &quot;marry&quot;
another, not only would he be committing adultery, but the person
he &quot;marries&quot; would likewise be committing adultery!
When we consider passages like 1 Cor. 6:9,10 and Rev. 21:8, we
can only conclude such will result in that person being thrown
into the lake of fire, that is, unless that adultery ceases and
they find forgiveness. </p>

<p>The Apostle Paul gave these instructions about remarriage: </p>

<p>&quot;To the married I give this command (not I, but the
Lord): A wife must not separate from her husband. But if she
does, SHE MUST REMAIN UNMARRIED OR ELSE BE RECONCILED TO HER
HUSBAND. And a husband must not divorce his wife. To the rest I
say this (I, not the Lord): If any brother has a wife who is not
a believer and she is willing to live with him, he must not
divorce her. And if a woman has a husband who is not a believer
and he is willing to live with her, she must not divorce him ...
But if the unbeliever leaves, let him do so. A believing man or
woman is not bound in such circumstances; God has called us to
live in peace&quot; (1 Cor. 7:10-15). </p>

<p>Paul stated the only other reason to divorce would be if one
spouse got saved and the other left because of it. Then the saved
spouse would be free to remarry. </p>

<p>(2) You may mention getting forgiven for &quot;divorcing our
spouses.&quot; Please know that there is no such thing in
Scripture as getting forgiven from the sin of divorce! This
subtle twisting of the Word regarding getting forgiven over the
sin of divorce has led some to go through with it, then remarry
another who really is not eligible for one reason or another. </p>

<p>(3) When Jesus spoke of committing adultery over an
illegitimate marriage as cited in Matt. 5:32; 19:9, a
CONTINUOUS-TENSE ADULTERY is what would result. This would be
impossible if one would illegitimately marry a person, then
&quot;repent&quot; of his sin of divorce and his sin of
illegitimate marriage and go on as if it was now a marriage
recognized by God. </p>

<p>(4) You may say you are so much in love and desire to serve
the Lord together as husband and wife. Such is an impossibility.
Neither of you two can ever be recognized from God's perspective
as bound together by Him as husband and wife! This statement,
though it may seem hard, is the truth, based on Scripture. The
best way for you two to serve the Lord is to begin to stop
entertaining the thought that you two would like to get married.
This is like two people saying &quot;We want to rob a bank and
then serve the Lord.&quot; </p>

<p>(5) To say you know of other &quot;Christian couples&quot; who
are both divorced and remarried and have good solid marriages and
serve the Lord well is irrelevant! What other people have or
don't have or do or don't do has nothing to do with us
individually. We are to go by the Word of God regardless if
anyone else goes by it or not. It seems like you are trying to
find every possible reason to &quot;marry&quot; outside of the
will of God to justify your action, even to the point of looking
at others who have done a similar thing. </p>

<p>Granted, there are many people who are illegitimately married.
Such are committing continuous adultery from God's perspective
and really are not &quot;Christian&quot; as they may profess to
be. It is impossible to be a Christian and to be sexually immoral
at the same time. There is no such thing as once saved always
saved. So if you think you can both divorce, then marry each
other and be spiritually safe, based upon eternal security, you
are Scripturally mistaken. Eternal security is a rampant heresy
that has multitudes in danger of Hell without such knowing
they're in this type of danger. [Please see our web site for
information exposing and refuting the heresy of eternal security
as well as many other topics of relevance to us all.] </p>

<p>This life is a test (Jam. 1:12; Rev. 2:10,11; 3:10). The
stakes are eternal. Only the minority will pass the test and
enter through the narrow gate that leads to life (Matt. 7:13,14).
The vast majority will be thrown into the lake of fire (Rev.
20:15; 21:8). Don't get yourself snared by an illegitimate
marriage that may bring much temporal pleasure and comfort now,
but reap an eternal torment in fire and great regret over such
later. </p>

<p>It is not always God's will to remarry as 1 Cor. 7:11 clearly
states. </p>

<p>Stay in the Bible and go by ITS counsel. Think beyond the
grave. </p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

