<body bgcolor="#FFFFCC" text="#000000">

<p>Subject: sleeping arrangements
</p>

<p><font face="Times New Roman">I'de have to agree that for now it is OK, but knowing what I know about child development (BS in Elem Ed, AS in Early Childhood Ed) I'de have to adjust that age down a bit from 10-12.<BR>

I'de say you are quickly approaching the age at which they should be seperated.  Think about whether you would want these children (or whether they would want to) undress in front of even close friends of this age.  Similar standards should be applied to brothers and sisters, because children learn modesty at about the time in thier lives that they need it.  If they are modest enough that they don't want to be seen by the other, then they should have their own space. However, I have to take this a step further, and ask why it is ok to put two girls (or boys) together, and not a boy and a girl, I roomed with a sister and hated having to undress with her in the room.  Each child's individual personality should be taken into account.  I know a family who had a 10 and 13 year old boy and girl (respectively) and they still roomed together and wouldn't have it any other, though the sister was quickly approaching a change.  The point is.. take the children, and their personality and maturity, and relationship with their sibling into account, bottom end 3-5 top end 10-12. Depends on ALOT of different things.  
</font></p>


